SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 1249
By Southerland
A RESOLUTION to commend James "Mack" Hughes for eighty
years of membership in the American Legion.
WHEREAS, it is most fitting that the members of this General Assembly should
acknowledge and applaud those community leaders who have served their fellow citizens with
integrity and devotion; and
WHEREAS, one such noteworthy person is James "Mack" Hughes of Greene County, a
veteran of World War II and longtime member of the American Legion; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Hughes, who marked his 100th birthday on November 14, 2025, was
recently recognized by the National American Legion Headquarters for eighty continuous years
of membership with the veterans organization; and
WHEREAS, Mack Hughes graduated from Ottway High School in 1943 and thereafter
joined the U.S. Army Air Corps; he attended pilot training in Dallas, Texas, and was transferred
to Miami, Florida, for additional training and then to Albany, Georgia, to a B-25 bomber training
facility; and
WHEREAS, he was part of a College Training Detachment at Presbyterian College in
Clinton, South Carolina, and was still in training when he heard the news that Germany had
surrendered and the war in Europe was over; and
WHEREAS, after two years of service in the U.S. Army Air Corps, Mr. Hughes was given
the option to discharge and did so on November 8, 1945, returning home to Greeneville, where
he met his future wife, Jewell; and
WHEREAS, Mack and Jewell Hughes secured jobs with the Federal Bureau of
Investigation, traveling to Washington, D.C., where they were wed and began their service with
SJR1249
018393
- 1 -

the Bureau; they were later transferred to the Bureau's field office in Charlotte, North Carolina;
and
WHEREAS, while his wife remained with the FBI throughout her entire working career,
Mack Hughes eventually departed the Bureau and accepted a job with the Motorola Company;
following their retirements, Mr. and Mrs. Hughes returned to their hometown of Greeneville; and
WHEREAS, Mack and Jewell Hughes enjoyed sixty-eight years of marriage, until Mrs.
Hughes's passing in 2016; the couple were blessed with a daughter, Cathy Hughes LaLonde,
and two grandchildren, Kellie Neve and Jon Michael; and
WHEREAS, Mack Hughes epitomizes the spirit and commitment that are characteristic
of a true Tennessean; and
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly find it appropriate to acknowledge
and applaud Mr. Hughes for his military service and his dedication to his fellow citizens on this
noteworthy occasion; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we commend James "Mack" Hughes for eighty
years of membership in the American Legion, extending our gratitude for his service to his
country and the citizens of Tennessee.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
